<head ><bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg004' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 4</bibl></head>
<p >(<name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name>, <title >First Philippic</title>, see also <name  n='oratory' type='ancientGenre'>Oratory</name>). This is a speech that <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name> gave at a meeting of the <term  sortKey='Assembly'>Assembly</term>, and then published later. He delivered this speech sometime before <date  when='-0351'>351 BCE</date> (source for date: <bibl >J.H. Vince, <title >Demosthenes I</title> [Cambridge, Mass.; Loeb Classical Library; 1930] 67</bibl>). This speech represents the first time that <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name> spoke first in a debate in the <term  sortKey='Assembly'>Assembly</term> (see <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg004:1' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 4.1</bibl>). The subject of the speech is <name  type='person'>Philip</name> of <placeName  key='Macedon'>Macedon</placeName>, who had been increasingly active in Greek affairs, particularly those of <placeName  key='Thrace'>Thrace</placeName> and <placeName  key='Euboea'>Euboea</placeName>. Macedonian ships had even captured some ships bringing food to <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName>. Here, <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name> urges the Athenians not to feel helpless in the face of <name  type='person'>Philip</name>’s strength, but to fight to protect Athenian interests (See also, <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg006' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 6</bibl>, <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg009' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 9</bibl>, <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg010' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 10</bibl>—all speeches urging opposition to <name  type='person'>Philip</name>). </p>
<byline >Christopher Blackwell</byline>
